  "prompt": "What is the difference between clause and provision?",
  "response": "The terms \"clause\" and \"provision\" are often used in legal, contractual, and formal documents, but they have specific meanings and uses:\n\n### Clause:\n- **Definition**: A clause is a distinct section or part of a legal document, contract, or agreement that addresses a specific point or topic. It can include terms, conditions, rights, and obligations that both parties must adhere to.\n- **Examples**: Types of clauses include \"indemnity clause,\" \"termination clause,\" \"confidentiality clause,\" etc.\n- **Function**: Clauses are usually numbered or clearly marked to make it easy to reference them within the document.\n\n### Provision:\n- **Definition**: A provision refers to a specific stipulation, requirement, or condition included within a clause, section, or the entire document. It defines the terms under which an agreement operates and may specify what is required or what will happen under certain circumstances.\n- **Examples**: A provision might state that one party must give notice before terminating a contract or define the payment terms.\n- **Function**: Provisions can exist within clauses, and multiple provisions can be found in a single clause.\n\n### In Summary:\n- A **clause** is a broader section of a document that contains various stipulations, whereas a **provision** is a specific requirement or condition that can be found within a clause. Essentially, all provisions are found within clauses, but not every clause contains provisions that stand alone.",
